<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<manifest xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
  xmlns:tools="http://schemas.android.com/tools">

  <application
    android:name="com.hedvig.android.app.HedvigApplication">
    <!--
    DEBUG-ONLY test harness for push notifications and FCM token handling.

    Firebase delivers pushes by binding this receiver from Google Play Services, so a real
    message never arrives through an Intent we can craft from the shell. Firebase also guards
    the receiver with a Google-signed permission, which blocks the `adb shell` uid from poking
    it. Re-declaring it here with android:permission="@null" drops that guard so we can hand-feed
    intents over ADB and exercise the real on-device code path (Metro-injected NotificationSenders,
    the WorkManager factory wiring, etc.) without a backend or a live FCM token.

    This removes a security guard, so it MUST stay debug-only: it lives in src/debug and never
    merges into staging/release builds. Do not move it to the main manifest.

    Note: an XML comment cannot contain a double-dash, so the adb string-extra flag (dash dash es)
    is written below as `- -es`. Remove the space between the dashes when you actually run them.

    Simulate an incoming notification (routes to PushNotificationService.onMessageReceived,
    which dispatches to the matching NotificationSender):
      adb shell am broadcast -n com.hedvig.dev.app/com.google.firebase.iid.FirebaseInstanceIdReceiver \
        -c com.hedvig.dev.app -a com.google.android.c2dm.intent.RECEIVE \
        - -es TYPE NEW_MESSAGE - -es title "Title" - -es body "Body"

    Simulate a token refresh (routes to PushNotificationService.onNewToken, which enqueues
    FCMTokenUploadWorker through the Metro-provided WorkerFactory):
      adb shell am broadcast -n com.hedvig.dev.app/com.google.firebase.iid.FirebaseInstanceIdReceiver \
        -c com.hedvig.dev.app -a com.google.firebase.messaging.NEW_TOKEN - -es token fake-token
    -->
    <receiver
      android:name="com.google.firebase.iid.FirebaseInstanceIdReceiver"
      android:exported="true"
      android:permission="@null"
      tools:replace="android:permission">
      <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="com.google.android.c2dm.intent.RECEIVE" />
        <category android:name="com.hedvig.dev.app" />
      </intent-filter>
    </receiver>
  </application>
</manifest>
